[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(7) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "There is one law for them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—That is, the same rule, as stated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:27-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", applies to both the sin offering and the trespass offering; hence what is omitted in the regulation of the one must be supplied from the directions given in the other.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:7-8",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 7:7-8",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "As is the sin-offering, so is the trespass-offering — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the matter following, for in other things they differed. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The priests shall have it — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That part of it which was by God allowed to the priest. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The priest shall have to himself the skin — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The note of Bishop Patrick is worth transcribing here: “All the flesh of the burnt-offerings being wholly consumed, as well as the fat upon the altar, there was nothing that could fall to the share of the priest but the skin, which is here given him for his pains. It was observed upon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 3:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that it is probable Adam himself offered the first sacrifice, and had the skin given him by God, to make the garments for him and his wife. In conformity to which the priests ever after had the skin of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "whole burnt-offerings ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for their portion; which was a custom among the Gentiles, (as well as the Jews,) who gave the skins of their sacrifices to their priests, when they were not burned with the sacrifices, as in some sin-offerings they were among the Jews, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and they employed them to a superstitious use, by lying upon them in their temples, in hopes to have future things revealed to them in their dreams. Of this we have a proof in Virgil’s seventh Æneid, line 86. See Dryden’s translation, 7:127.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "7:1-10 In the sin-offering and the trespass-offering, the sacrifice was divided between the altar and the priest; the offerer had no share, as he had in the peace-offerings. The former expressed repentance and sorrow for sin, therefore it was more proper to fast than feast; the peace-offerings denoted communion with a reconciled God in Christ, the joy and gratitude of a pardoned sinner, and the privileges of a true believer.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
