  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 7-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " contain a general precept or note as to the priests' portion in the sin offering, trespass offering, burnt offering, and meat offering. The officiating priest was to have the flesh of the trespass offering and of the sin offering (except the fat burnt on the altar), and the skin of the burnt offering and the cooked meat offerings (except ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the memorial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " burnt on the altar), while the meat offerings of flour and of parched grains, which could be kept longer, were to be the property ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "of the priestly body in general, all the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " sons of Aaron,...  one as much as another. The skins of the peace offerings were retained by the offerer ('Mishna, Sebaeh,' 12, 3). Leviticus 7:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The fat portions only were to be burned upon the altar, viz., the same as in the sin and peace-offerings (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but the flesh was to be eaten by the priests, as in the sin-offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), inasmuch as there was the same law in this respect for both the sin-offering and trespass-offering; and these parts of the sacrificial service must therefore have had the same meaning, every trespass being a sin (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - Certain analogous instructions respecting the burnt-offering and meat-offering are appended in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:8-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " by way of supplement, as they ought properly to have been given in ch. 6, in the laws relating to the sacrifices in question.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
